Whatever the reason for the broken pipe, the fact remains that the client can no longer continue the http connection and communication on it.
Therefore the only logical reaction by the server should be to discontinue the communication by exiting the process.
```
    @ExceptionHandler(value = {IOException.class})
    @ResponseStatus(HttpStatus.SERVICE_UNAVAILABLE)
    public Object exceptionHandler(IOException e, WebRequest request) {
        if (StringUtils.containsIgnoreCase(ExceptionUtils.getRootCauseMessage(e), &quot;Broken pipe&quot;)) {
            return null;
        } else {
            return ... (your normal error response for IOException)
        }
    }
```
Thanks [Tarik Yurt][1]


  [1]: https://mtyurt.net/post/spring-how-to-handle-ioexception-broken-pipe.html

